(1)
In male imago, the terminal (3rd) segment of gonostylus has unique structure: it is hooked and pointed; cuticle of its outer side (directed caudally) is thick, rigid, smooth and sharply convex, while cuticle of its other sides is thin and rugose (
Figs 60–61
). In subimago, the terminal segment of gonostylus is also pointed, with larger outer side and smaller inner side (
Fig. 66
), but its subimaginal cuticle is entirely thin and covered with microtrichia, as are other gonostylar segments and most of other body parts. This shape of the terminal gonostylar segment is already expressed in subimaginal gonostyli which are crumpled under larval cuticle before moult to subimago (
Figs 57–58
, 
65
).

(12)
Larval tibiae of all legs without outer-apical stout seta (in contrast to many other 
Baetidae
). Tibia [lacking patella-tibial suture – see (3)] with small pointed spine-like setae on outer side and longer spine-like setae on inner side (
Fig. 32
).

(14) Tergalii of all pairs I–VII are wide, with anal rib poorly developed or absent ( Figs 5 , 45–51 ). Tergalii are capable of for rhythmical respiratory movements, that allows larva to inhabit places with stagnant water (observed for
D. crassi
).
